  <h2>About Dār al-Ḥaqq</h2>

  <p>Dār al-Ḥaqq is a small, English-language reader of traditional Sunnī replies to common Salafī claims. Each topic is built around quoted excerpts from authoritative answers on SeekersGuidance, IslamQA.org, Ask Imam, and hadithanswers.com — the work belongs to those scholars and sites. Dār al-Ḥaqq simply gathers and frames it.</p>

  <p>The site is maintained by a student of traditional Sunnī ʿilm. It is not original fatwa, has no editorial board, and should not be taken as a replacement for asking a qualified scholar in your locality. Where the framing prose makes a claim that is not directly cited, treat it as the maintainer's reading of the broader Ashʿarī / Māturīdī tradition — verify with your shaykh.</p>

  <p>To suggest a topic, correct an error, or flag a misattributed quote, <a href="https://github.com/YusefB/darulhaqq/issues/new" rel="noopener external">open an issue on GitHub</a>. Corrections are taken seriously.</p>

  <h3 id="how-written">How this site is written</h3>

  <p>To be transparent about what's mine and what's not:</p>

  <p><strong>Quoted excerpts are verbatim.</strong> Every passage rendered in a quote box (gold left rule, with author and source attributed below) is a direct quotation from the cited URL or printed work. These are not paraphrased, not AI-generated, and not edited. Where the source is a website, the link goes to the live page; where the source is a printed book, the page or section is named.</p>

  <p><strong>Framing prose is AI-drafted, maintainer-edited.</strong> The connective text — page summaries, the "Salafī position" / "classical Sunnī position" / "Where the Salafī position runs into difficulty" sections on each topic, the scholar biographies and methodology entries, the historical narrative on the homepage, the comparative essays on ʿAqīdah differences and Methodology — was drafted with the help of an AI assistant (Anthropic's Claude) and then reviewed and edited by the maintainer before publishing. It is intended to summarise and frame the cited sources fairly; it is not original scholarship and should not be cited as such.</p>

  <p>The reason for the split: the maintainer is a student, not a muftī, and the goal of the site is to surface and organise the actual scholarly literature. AI is a useful tool for drafting the structural prose and keeping the tone consistent across many pages — but the religious authority of any claim on this site rests entirely on the verbatim source it is drawn from, not on the framing around it. When in doubt, click the source link, read the original, and ask a qualified scholar.</p>

  <p>If you find a place where the framing prose misrepresents what a cited source actually says, that's the most important kind of correction — please open an issue.</p>
